04366nam a22005895i 9780773590977DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735909777 a10.1515/97807735909772doi  a(DE-B1597)656761  a(OCoLC)820839325  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a333.91/41509714141 aMassell, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQuebec Hydropolitics :bThe Peribonka Concessions of the Second World War /cDavid Massell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Quebec/Études d'histoire du Québec00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tHydraulic Hinterland, Native Home: A Prehistory -- tLac Manouan -- tPasse Dangereuse -- tBeyond Quebec: The Shipshaw-Massena Bargain -- t“Do We Live in the Province of Aluminum or in the Province of Quebec?” -- tBersimis and Beyond -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe construction in the 1940s of hydroelectric dams and reservoirs, Lakes Manouan and Passe Dangereuse, were enormous projects that had consequences not only on the environment but also on international affairs. Built by the Aluminium Company of Canada (Rio Tinto Alcan), the project helped meet the American and Allied Forces demand for electrical power and aluminium ingot during the Second World War but also forced Innu/Montagnais hunter-trappers from their ancestral lands. Examining sources as varied as the papers of the Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and interviews with Montagnais elders, Quebec Hydropolitics presents a compelling synthesis of business and social history as well as wartime politics. David Massell reconstructs the story of a changing landscape through the perspectives of corporate executives, government officials, and Aboriginals to show the effect that war had on Canadian resource extraction and energy policy as well as its indigenous peoples. A narrative that flows from the Saguenay watershed to the centres of political power, Quebec Hydropolitics is an informative look at the costs and benefits of large-scale industrialization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConcessions -- Québec (Province) -- Péribonka River Region -- History. 0aIndustrialization -- Québec (Province) -- Péribonka River Region -- History. 0aMontagnais Indians -- Québec (Province) -- Peribonka River Region. 0aPéribonka River Region (Québec) -- History. 0aQuebec (Province) -- Politics and government -- 1936-1960. 0aWater resources development -- Political aspects -- Québec (Province) -- Peribonka River Region -- History. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945 -- Québec (Province) -- Péribonka River Region. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359097740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773590977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773590977/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles